1 Requirements for teXtWiki
A statement of requirements to modify XWiki to create teXtWiki to support the [Global Text Project>http://globaltext.org].
1.1 Roles and privileges
{table} Role |Privileges |Login required Reader |Read, search |No Contributor |Propose changes, search |Yes Chapter editor |Chapter editing, accept change, search and replace across a chapter |Yes Book editor |Book editing, chapter creation, search and replace across a book |Yes Field editor |Field editing, book creation, search and replace across a field |Yes Library editor |Library editing, field creation, search and replace across a library |Yes {table}
1.1 Data model
XWiki’s basic structural unit is a page, whereas we want to create books with chapters and sections. While one can create a book using the software, it does not support a data structure equivalent to a book or a library. Searching, for instance, cannot be confined to within a single book. Searching across the entire library, or all the books in a field (e.g., biology), must be supported. An initial data model is shown in Exhibit 1.
*Exhibit 1. Data model for teXtWiki*
{image:erdv3}
1.1 Tag extensions
XWiki has the facility to add new tags similar to {xml} and these will be very useful, for example
* {textbox, type="y", bgcolor="color"} ** y might be case, chapter summary, section summary, example ** alternatively, the tags might have fixed attribute (e.g., {case}) for consistency ** Use [docbook>http://www.docbook.org/] tags as a guide for what might be required * {keyterm} ** keyterm and its definition, which is viewable by a mouse-over * {exhibit} and {reference} ** See following discussion
1.1 Access control & color coding
A fundamental feature of a wiki is that anyone can modify a page. While we strongly support this principle, we want to introduce a modification that we think is necessary for a textbook. As each chapter will have an editor, who is an authority on the topic, we want to indicate which modifications a chapter’s editors have not yet approved, through means such as color-coding. For example, the regular text would have a white background, and unapproved additions would have a light yellow background. Thus, readers would be alerted to be cautious when reading unapproved text, but we would not lose the spontaneity and participative nature of a wiki.
1.1 Automatic numbering of exhibits
* We have decided to dispense with figures, tables, etc. and just use the general term exhibit * Automatic numbering of exhibits and the corresponding cross references increases author productivity * Exhibits should be numbered as x.y, where x is the chapter and y the exhibit within the chapter ** Initial implementation should be numbering within a chapter
1.1 Key terms
Readers should be able to mouse over key terms (tagged with {keyterm}) to get a definition of the term. This should obviate the need for a glossary for a book, and the key terms could be harvested to create a glossary for a field.
1.1 Search and replace
Support search and replace across a library, book, chapter, or section.
1.1 Spell checking
Desirable for the editor, and should be readily available as a java object. [JBossWiki>http://labs.jboss.com/portal/jbosswiki] has a spellchecker. Also JBossWiki is Java based and JSR 168 compliant.
In line with the United Nations, the Oxford English Dictionary is the standard for spelling.
1.1 Languages
Support for Arabic, Chinese, and Spanish is required.
1.1 Mathematics
[MathML>http://www.w3.org/Math/] must be supported.
